<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870612-0073 </DOCNO><HL> Three Banks in KansasAnd Texas Are Closed</HL><DD> 06/12/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> GOVMTBANKS, THRIFT INSTITUTIONS (BNK)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE) </IN><DATELINE> WASHINGTON  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Three banks in Texas and Kansas were closed yesterday, bringing the number of bank failures this year to 88, the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. said.    The failed institutions are Northwest Commercial Bank, Houston, which had assets of $12.1 million; Benton State Bank, Benton, Kan., which had assets of $9.1 million, and First State Bank, Milford, Texas, which had assets of $6.6 million.    Depositors at Northwest Commercial, closed by the U.S. Comptroller of the Currency, will automatically become depositors at Jersey Village Bank, Houston, beginning today. Northwest Commercial's two offices won't reopen. The failed bank held $12.1 million in 1,600 deposit accounts.    Benton State, closed by state banking regulators, is to reopen today as a branch of First National Bank andamp; Trust Co., El Dorado, Kan. Benton State held $8.4 million in 2,100 deposit accounts and was the third Kansas bank to fail this year.    First State, closed by state regulators, is to reopen today as Ellis County State Bank, a newly chartered institution. First State held deposits of $6.4 million in 1,400 accounts.    A total of 31 banks have failed in Texas this year. </TEXT></DOC>